properties.Name: EEZ (from coastal baseline/shoreline)
properties.Description:
China’s claim to an exclusive economic zone (EEZ), as set out in 1998 legislation, notes that:

“claims regarding the exclusive economic zone and the continental shelf by the People’s Republic of China and States with opposite or adjacent coasts shall be settled, on the basis of international law and in accordance with the principle of equity, by an agreement delimiting the areas so claimed”.

In general, we have used equidistant median lines where China’s claims overlapped with other countries’ EEZ claims, except where public information suggests that China has favored a different principle for delimitation.

China and South Korea are currently in negotiations to delimit their maritime boundary in the Yellow Sea. Based on reporting of their negotiating positions, South Korea favors beginning adjustments from an equidistant line, while China prefers a line that takes into consideration the relative lengths of the two countries’ coastlines, following an equitable distribution principle. The maritime overlap between the two proposals covers a submerged feature, Ieodo, presently controlled by South Korea. While both sides claim that Ieodo falls within their EEZ, they agree that the feature itself cannot generate an EEZ. For now, pending further detail on China’s claim, we used an equidistant line to illustrate this boundary.

An important exception to the median-line usage is along China’s EEZ boundary with Japan, where it has acted in the past as if it exercises sovereignty over a full 200-nm EEZ. Around the Diaoyu/Senkaku Islands, the EEZ is drawn to its full extent from the coast, taking into consideration several 200-nm points claimed in a preliminary information submission to the Commission on the Limits of the Continental Shelf.

Other places where a median line has been used include the boundary with North Korea, between the EEZ generated by Pratas Island and the Philippines, and southwest of the Paracel Islands along the boundary with Vietnam’s EEZ. We treated the waters around Pratas Island as part of Taiwan’s claim and, implicitly, part of China’s claimed maritime area.
